# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alphasatellitidae
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alphasatellitidae/ackermannviridae] The family's name, *Ackermann* is in honor of Hans-Wolfgang Ackermann (1936–2017), a German microbiologist, the suffix *-viridae* is the standard suffix for virus families.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenine] Adenine has a central role in cellular respiration.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenine] It is part of adenosine triphosphate which provides the energy that drives and supports most activities in living cells, such as protein synthesis, muscle contraction, and nerve impulse propagation.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenine] In respiration it also participates as part of the cofactors nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide, flavin adenine dinucleotide, and coenzyme A.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenine] It is also part of adenosine, adenosine monophosphate, cyclic adenosine monophosphate, adenosine diphosphate, and S-adenosylmethionine.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenine] Adenine forms several tautomers, compounds that can be rapidly interconverted and are often considered equivalent.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenine] However, in isolated conditions, i.e. in an inert gas matrix and in the gas phase, mainly the 9H-adenine tautomer is found.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenine] Purine metabolism involves the formation of adenine and guanine.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenine] Both adenine and guanine are derived from the nucleotide inosine monophosphate (IMP), which in turn is synthesized from a pre-existing ribose phosphate through a complex pathway using atoms from the amino acids glycine, glutamine, and aspartic acid, as well as the coenzyme tetrahydrofolate.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenine] Patented August 20, 1968, the current recognized method of industrial-scale production of adenine involves heating formamide under 120 °C.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenine] Adenine is one of the two purine nucleobases (the other being guanine) used in forming nucleotides of the nucleic acids.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenine] In DNA, adenine binds to thymine via two hydrogen bonds to assist in stabilizing the nucleic acid structures.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenine] In RNA, which is used for protein synthesis, adenine binds to uracil.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenine] Adenine forms adenosine, a nucleoside, when attached to ribose, and deoxyadenosine when attached to deoxyribose.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenine] It forms adenosine triphosphate (ATP), a nucleoside triphosphate, when three phosphate groups are added to adenosine.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenine] Adenosine triphosphate is used in cellular metabolism as one of the basic methods of transferring chemical energy between chemical reactions.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenine] ATP is thus a derivative of adenine, adenosine, cyclic adenosine monophosphate, and adenosine diphosphate.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenine] In older literature, adenine was sometimes called **Vitamin B4**, but is no longer considered a vitamin.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenine] Due to it being synthesized by the body and not essential to be obtained by diet, it does not meet the definition of vitamin and is no longer part of the Vitamin B complex.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenine] However, two B vitamins, niacin and riboflavin, bind with adenine to form the essential cofactors nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide (NAD) and flavin adenine dinucleotide (FAD), respectively.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenine] Hermann Emil Fischer was one of the early scientists to study adenine.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenine] It was named in 1885 by Albrecht Kossel after Greek *ἀδήν* aden "gland", in reference to the pancreas, from which Kossel's sample had been extracted.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenine] Adenine can be prepared from ammonia and hydrogen cyanide (HCN) in aqueous solution, a process that has implications for the origin of life on Earth.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenine] On August 8, 2011, a report, based on NASA studies with meteorites found on Earth, was published suggesting building blocks of DNA and RNA (adenine, guanine and related organic molecules) may have been formed extraterrestrially in outer space.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] They have a broad range of vertebrate hosts; in humans, more than 50 distinct adenoviral serotypes have been found to cause a wide range of illnesses, from mild respiratory infections in young children (the common cold) to life-threatening multi-organ disease in people with a weakened immune system.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] All these types are called Human mastadenovirus A–G by the ICTV, because all are members of the genus *Mastadenovirus*.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] Adenoviruses are medium-sized (90–100 nm).
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] The virions are composed of one linear piece of double-stranded DNA inside an icosahedral capsid.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] 240 hexon proteins make up the bulk of the capsid, while twelve penton bases cap the icosahedron's corners.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] The penton bases are associated with protruding fibers that aid in attachment to the host cell via the receptor on its surface.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] In 2010, the structure of the human adenovirus was solved at the atomic level, making it the largest high-resolution model ever.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] The virus is composed of around 1 million amino acid residues and weighs around 150 MDa.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] The adenovirus genome is linear, non-segmented double-stranded (ds) DNA that is between 26 and 48 kbp.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] This allows the virus to theoretically carry 22 to 40 genes.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] Although this is significantly larger than other viruses in its Baltimore group, it is still a very simple virus and is heavily reliant on the host cell for survival and replication.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] The genes of adenoviruses can generally be divided into well-conserved sets of transcription units with six early transcription units (E1A, E1B, E2A, E2B, E3 and E4) and one late transcription unit ranging from L1-L5.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] In addition, adenoviruses also contain two intermediate transcription units named XI and IVa2.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] To increase the viral gene economy, adenoviruses accommodate genes on both strands of its dsDNA meaning that most of its genome is utilized for coding proteins.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] An interesting feature of this viral genome is that it has a terminal 55 kDa protein associated with each of the 5' ends of the linear dsDNA.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] These are used as primers in viral replication and ensure that the ends of the virus' linear genome are adequately replicated.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] Adenoviruses possess a linear dsDNA genome and are able to replicate in the nucleus of vertebrate cells using the host's replication machinery.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] Entry of adenoviruses into the host cell involves two sets of interactions between the virus and the host cell.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] Most of the action occurs at the vertices.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] Entry into the host cell is initiated by the knob domain of the fiber protein binding to the cell receptor.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] The two currently established receptors are: CD46 for the group B human adenovirus serotypes and the coxsackievirus/adenovirus receptor (CAR) for all other serotypes.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] There are some reports suggesting MHC molecules and sialic acid residues functioning in this capacity as well.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] This is followed by a secondary interaction, where a motif in the penton base protein (see capsomere) interacts with an integrin molecule.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] It is the co-receptor interaction that stimulates entry of the adenovirus.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] This co-receptor molecule is αV integrin.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] Binding to αV integrin results in endocytosis of the virus particle via clathrin-coated pits.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] Attachment to αV integrin stimulates cell signaling and thus induces actin polymerization, which facilitates clathrin-mediated endocytosis, and results in virion's entry into the host cell within an endosome.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] Once the virus has successfully gained entry into the host cell, the endosome acidifies, which alters virus topology by causing capsid components to disband.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] The capsid is destabilized and protein VI, which is one of the capsid constituents (see Adenovirus genome) is released from it.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] Protein VI contains an N-terminal amphiphatic alpha-helix, a helical domain that exhibits both hydrophobic and hydrophilic properties.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] This amphipathic helix enables the binding of protein VI to the endosomal membrane leading to a severe membrane curvature that ultimately disrupts the endosome.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] These changes, as well as the toxic nature of the pentons, destroy the endosome, resulting in the movement of the virion into the cytoplasm.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] With the help of cellular microtubules, the virus is transported to the nuclear pore complex, whereby the adenovirus particle disassembles.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] Viral DNA is subsequently released, which can enter the nucleus via the nuclear pore.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] After this the DNA associates with histone molecules already present in the nucleus, which allows it to interact with the host cell transcription machinery.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] Then, viral gene expression can occur, without integrating the viral genome into host cell chromosomes, and new virus particles can be generated.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] The adenovirus life cycle is separated by the DNA replication process into two phases: an early and a late phase.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] In both phases, a primary transcript that is alternatively spliced to generate monocistronic mRNAs compatible with the host's ribosome is generated, allowing for the products to be translated.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] The early genes are responsible for expressing mainly non-structural, regulatory proteins.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] Some adenoviruses under specialized conditions can transform cells using their early gene products.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] E1A (binds Retinoblastoma tumor suppressor protein) has been found to immortalize primary cells *in vitro* allowing E1B (binds p53 tumor suppressor) to assist and stably transform the cells.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] Nevertheless, they are reliant upon each other to successfully transform the host cell and form tumors.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] E1A is mostly intrinsically disordered protein and contains CR3 domain which is critical for transcriptional activation.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] DNA replication separates the early and late phases.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] Once the early genes have liberated adequate virus proteins, replication machinery, and replication substrates, replication of the adenovirus genome can occur.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] A terminal protein that is covalently bound to the 5' end of the adenovirus genome acts as a primer for replication.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] The viral DNA polymerase then uses a strand displacement mechanism, as opposed to the conventional Okazaki fragments used in mammalian DNA replication, to replicate the genome.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] The late phase of the adenovirus lifecycle is focused on producing sufficient quantities of structural protein to pack all the genetic material produced by DNA replication.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] Once the viral components have successfully been replicated, the virus is assembled into its protein shells and released from the cell as a result of virally induced cell lysis.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] Adenovirus is capable of multiplicity reactivation (MR) (Yamamoto and Shimojo, 1971).
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] MR is the process by which two, or more, virus genomes that have been damaged to the point of nonviability interact within the infected cell to form a viable virus genome.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] Such MR was demonstrated for adenovirus 12 after virions were irradiated with UV light and allowed to undergo multiple infection of host cells.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] In a review, numerous examples of MR in different viruses were described, and it was suggested that MR is a common form of sexual interaction that provides the survival advantage of recombinational repair of genome damages.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] Adenoviruses are unusually stable to chemical or physical agents and adverse pH conditions, allowing for prolonged survival outside of the body and water.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] Adenoviruses are spread primarily via respiratory droplets, however they can also be spread by fecal routes and via aerosols (airborne transmission).
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] Research into the molecular mechanisms underlying adenoviral transmission provide empirical evidence in support of the hypothesis that coxsackievirus/adenovirus receptors (CARs) are needed to transport adenoviruses into certain naive/progenitor cell types.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] Humans infected with adenoviruses display a wide range of responses, from no symptoms at all to the severe infections typical of Adenovirus serotype 14.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] Bat adenovirus TJM (Bt-AdV-TJM) is a novel species of the *Mastadenovirus* genus isolated from *Myotis* and *Scotophilus kuhlii* in China.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] It is most closely related to the tree shrew and canine AdVs.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] Two types of canine adenoviruses are well known, type 1 and 2.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] Type 1 (CAdV-1) causes infectious canine hepatitis, a potentially fatal disease involving vasculitis and hepatitis.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] Type 1 infection can also cause respiratory and eye infections.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] CAdV-1 also affects foxes (*Vulpes vulpes* and *Vulpes lagopus*) and may cause hepatitis and encephalitis.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] *Canine adenovirus 2* (CAdV-2) is one of the potential causes of kennel cough.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] Core vaccines for dogs include attenuated live CAdV-2, which produces immunity to CAdV-1 and CAdV-2.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] CAdV-1 was initially used in a vaccine for dogs, but corneal edema was a common complication.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] Squirrel adenovirus (SqAdV) is reported to cause enteritis in red squirrels in Europe, while gray squirrels seem to be resistant.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] SqAdV is most closely related to the adenovirus of guinea pigs (GpAdV).
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] Adenovirus in reptiles is poorly understood, but research is currently in progress.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] Adenoviruses are also known to cause respiratory infections in horses, cattle, pigs, sheep, and goats.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] *Equine adenovirus 1* can also cause fatal disease in immunocompromised Arabian foals, involving pneumonia and destruction of pancreatic and salivary gland tissue.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] *Tupaia adenovirus* (TAV) (tree shrew adenovirus 1) has been isolated from tree shrews.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] Otarine adenovirus 1 has been isolated from sea lions (*Zalophus californianus*).
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] The fowl adenoviruses are associated with many disease conditions in domestic fowl like inclusion body hepatitis, hydropericardium syndrome, egg drop syndrome, quail bronchitis, and gizzard erosions.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] They have also been isolated from wild black kites (*Milvus migrans*).
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] Titi monkey adenovirus was isolated from a colony of monkeys.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] Currently there is a vaccine for adenovirus type 4 and 7 for US military personnel only.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] US military personnel are the recipients of this vaccine because they may be at a higher risk of infection.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] The vaccine contains a live virus, which may be shed in stool and lead to transmission.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] The vaccine is not approved for use outside of the military, as it has not been tested in studied in the general population or on people with weakened immune systems.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] In the past, US military recruits were vaccinated against two serotypes of adenovirus, with a corresponding decrease in illnesses caused by those serotypes.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] Army Medical Research and Materiel Command announced on 31 October 2011 that a new adenovirus vaccine, which replaces the older version that has been out of production for over a decade, was shipped to basic training sites on 18 October 2011.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] Prevention of adenovirus, as well as other respiratory illnesses, involves frequent hand washing for more than 20 seconds, avoiding touching the eyes, face, and nose with unwashed hands, and avoiding close contact with people with symptomatic adenovirus infection.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] Those with symptomatic adenovirus infection are additionally advised to cough or sneeze into the arm or elbow instead of the hand, to avoid sharing cups and eating utensils, and to refrain from kissing others.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] Chlorination of swimming pools can prevent outbreaks of conjunctivitis caused by adenovirus.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] Tests are only necessary in very serious cases.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] Tests include blood tests, eyes, nose or throat swabs, stool sample tests, and chest x-rays.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] In the laboratory, adenovirus can be identified with antigen detection, polymerase chain reaction (PCR), virus isolation and serology.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] Even if adenovirus is found to be present, it may not be the cause of any symptoms.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] Some immunocompromised individuals can shed the virus for weeks and show no symptoms.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] Most infections with adenovirus result in infections of the upper respiratory tract.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] Adenovirus infections often present as conjunctivitis, tonsillitis (which may look exactly like strep throat and cannot be distinguished from strep except by throat culture), an ear infection, or croup.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] Adenoviruses types 40 and 41 can also cause gastroenteritis.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] A combination of conjunctivitis and tonsillitis is particularly common with adenovirus infections.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] Some children (especially the youngest) can develop adenovirus bronchiolitis or pneumonia, both of which can be severe.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] In babies, adenoviruses can also cause coughing fits that look almost exactly like whooping cough.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] Adenoviruses can also cause viral meningitis or encephalitis.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] Rarely, adenovirus can cause hemorrhagic cystitis (inflammation of the urinary bladder—a form of urinary tract infection—with blood in the urine).
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] Most people recover from adenovirus infections by themselves, but people with immunodeficiency sometimes die of adenovirus infections, and—rarely—even previously healthy people can die of these infections.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] This may be because sometimes adenoviral infection can lead to cardiac disorders.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] For example, in one study, some cardiac samples of patients with dilated cardiomyopathy were positive for presence of adenovirus type 8.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] Adenoviruses are often transmitted by expectoration (e.g. aerosols), but they can also be transmitted by contact with an infected person, or by virus particles left on objects such as towels and faucet handles.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] Some people with adenovirus gastroenteritis may shed the virus in their stools for months after getting over the symptoms.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] The virus can be passed through water in swimming pools that are not sufficiently chlorinated.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] As with many other illnesses, good handwashing practice is one way to inhibit the person-to-person transmission of adenoviruses.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] Heat and bleach will kill adenoviruses on objects.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] There are no proven antiviral drugs to treat adenoviral infections, so treatment is largely directed at the symptoms (such as acetaminophen for fever).
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] The antiviral drug cidofovir has helped certain of those patients who had severe cases of illness; the number helped and to what degree, and the particular complications or symptoms it helped with, and when and where this happened, were not given in the source.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] A doctor may give antibiotic eyedrops for conjunctivitis, while awaiting results of bacterial cultures, and to help prevent secondary bacterial infections.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] Currently, there is no adenovirus vaccine available to the general public, but a vaccine is available for the United States military for Types 4 and 7.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] Adenoviruses have long been a popular viral vector for gene therapy due to their ability to affect both replicating and non-replicating cells, accommodate large transgenes, and code for proteins without integrating genetic material into the host cell genome.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] More specifically, they are used as a vehicle to administer targeted therapy, in the form of recombinant DNA or protein.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] This therapy has been found especially useful in treating monogenic disease (e.g. cystic fibrosis, X-linked SCID, alpha1-antitrypsin deficiency) and cancer.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] In China, oncolytic adenovirus is an approved cancer treatment.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] Other oncolytic viruses are also under development, aimed at a range of additional solid tumor types .
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] Specific modifications on fiber proteins are used to target Adenovirus to certain cell types; a major effort is made to limit hepatotoxicity and prevent multiple organ failure.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] Adenovirus dodecahedron can qualify as a potent delivery platform for foreign antigens to human myeloid dendritic cells (MDC), and that it is efficiently presented by MDC to M1-specific CD8+ T lymphocytes.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] A safety issue with adenoviruses is that they can cause an immune response with a related inflammatory response as occurred in the death of Jesse Gelsinger in 1999.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] To address this risk, the genome of the virus has been modified to remove some viral genes.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] One such modification is the gutless vector that removes almost all the viral genome.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] Adenovirus has been used for delivery of CRISPR/Cas9 gene editing systems, but high immune reactivity to viral infection has posed challenges in use for patients.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] Modified (recombinant) adenovirus vectors, including replication incompetent types, can deliver DNA coding for specific antigens.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] Adenovirus have been used to produce viral vector COVID-19 vaccines.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] Ad5... serves as the 'vector' to transport the surface protein gene of SARS-CoV-2".
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] The goal is to genetically express the spike glycoprotein of severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2 (SARS-CoV-2).
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] A replication-deficient chimpanzee adenovirus vaccine vector (ChAdOx1) is used by the Oxford–AstraZeneca COVID-19 vaccine that has been approved for use.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] The Janssen COVID-19 vaccine uses modified recombinant adenovirus type-26 (Ad26).
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] Recombinant adenovirus type-5 (Ad5) are being used by Ad5-nCoV, ImmunityBio and UQ-CSL V451.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] The Gam-COVID-Vac (aka Sputnik-V) product is innovative because an Ad26 based vaccine is used on the first day and an Ad5 vaccine is used on day 21.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] Another one is *ChAd-SARS-CoV-2-S*; the vaccine reportedly prevented mice that were genetically modified to have human ACE2 (hACE2) receptors, presumably receptors that allow virus-entry into the cells, from being infected with SARS-CoV-2.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] Possible issues with using Adenovirus as vaccine vectors include: the human body develops immunity to the vector itself, making subsequent booster shots difficult or impossible.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] In some cases, people have pre-existing immunity to Adenoviruses, making vector delivery ineffective.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] The use of Ad5 vaccines for COVID-19 worried researchers who had experience with two failed trials of an Ad5 vaccine, Phambili and STEP, due to the increased risk for uncircumcised male patients of contracting HIV-1 via unprotected anal sex.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] At the time, it was concluded that heightened risk of HIV reception may be observed for any Ad5-based vector vaccine.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] Two studies found that Ad5-specific CD4 T cells are more susceptible to HIV infection than CD4 T cells specific to certain other vectors, such as Cytomegalovirus and Canarypox.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] By comparison, a *Science* article reported that China had approved CanSino's Ebola vaccine based on an Ad5 vector.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] It was tested in Sierra Leone, which had high HIV prevalence, making it more likely for such problems to be detected.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] CanSino's CEO said "we haven't seen anything with the Ebola vaccine" and speculated that HIV susceptibility might be limited to Ad5 vaccines which produced HIV proteins.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adenoviridae] In research reported in *The Lancet* in May, the company's researchers acknowledged the possibility, called it "controversial" and said they would watch for it in the company's COVID-19 vaccine candidate's trials.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] The extracellular particles (virions) of adnavirians consist of the genome encased in capsid proteins to form a helical nucleoprotein complex.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] For some of them, this helix is surrounded by a lipid membrane called an envelope.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] Some contain an additional protein layer between the nucleoprotein helix and the envelope.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] Complete virions are long and thin and may be flexible or stiff like a rod.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] In general, enveloped adnavirians are more flexible than non-enveloped ones.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] At both ends of the virion are protrusions involved in host recognition.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] Viruses in the realm use a variety of methods to replicate their genomes and rely on host machinery for transcription.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] Virions are assembled and enveloped in the host cell's cytoplasm.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] Their A-DNA genome is formed by interactions between pre-genomic B-DNA and the MCP and may be an adaptation to extremely high temperatures.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] They are lytic viruses, leaving their host through ruptures in the cell's external membrane (lysis).
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] Adnavirians may have infected the last archaeal common ancestor.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] In general, they have no genetic relation to viruses outside the realm.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] They were first discovered in the 1980s by Wolfram Zillig and his colleagues.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] Since its discovery in 1988, the adnavirian Sulfolobus islandicus rod-shaped virus 2 (SIRV2) has become a model for studying virus-host interactions in archaea.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] The realm *Adnaviria* was established in 2021 after cryogenic electron microscopy showed that member viruses shared their A-DNA, MCP, and general virion structure.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] Viruses in *Adnaviria* have linear, double-stranded DNA (dsDNA) genomes that range from about 17.6 to 41.5 kilobase pairs in length.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] The ends of their genomes contain inverted terminal repeats.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] Their genomes exist in A-form, also called A-DNA, a dehydrated version of the more typical B-form DNA.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] A-DNA has a compact right-handed helix with more base pairs per turn than B-DNA, and the base pairs in A-DNA are not perpendicular to the DNA's helix axis.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] The creation of genomic A-DNA is caused by major capsid protein (MCP) dimers interacting with the phosphodiester bond DNA backbone during virion assembly, covering pre-genomic B-DNA to form a helical nucleoprotein complex that contains genomic A-DNA.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] The A-form genome may be an adaptation to extremely high temperatures.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] The nucleoprotein helix is composed of asymmetric units of two MCPs.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] For rudiviruses, this is a homodimer, a molecule formed by the bonding of two identical MCPs.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] For other adnavirians, it is a heterodimer, a molecule formed by the bonding of two structurally similar MCPs that are paralogous.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] The MCPs of viruses in *Adnaviria* have a folded structure that contains an alpha-helix bundle that has four helices, called the SIRV2 fold, named after Sulfolobus islandicus rod-shaped virus 2 (SIRV2).
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] The four-helix bundle is found at the end (C-terminus) of the protein, while the beginning (N-terminus) of the protein has an extended alpha-helical arm that, when a part of MCP dimers, forms a closed claw-like shape that wraps tightly around the dsDNA genome to change it to A-form.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] Variations in the protein structure exist, but the same base structure is retained in all adnavirians.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] The MCP genes are the only core genes found in all viruses in the realm.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] The extracellular bodies (virions) of adnavirians are filamentous, i.e., they are long, thin, and cylindrical.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] Virions are about 400–2,000 nanometers (nm) in length and 24–38 nm in diameter.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] Lipothrixviruses and ungulaviruses have flexible virions in which the nucleoprotein helix is surrounded by a lipid envelope.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] Tristromaviruses likewise have flexible, enveloped virions with an additional protein sheath layer between the nucleoprotein complex and the envelope.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] Envelopes are half as thick as the host cell membrane as they are derived from host diether and tetraether lipids that either are short (archaeol) or can be bent into a U shape.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] Rudviruses have stiff, non-enveloped, rod-like virions about 600–900 by 23 nm.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] Non-enveloped adnavirians are more rigid, while enveloped adnavirians are more flexible.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] At both ends of the virion, lipothrixviruses and ungulaviruses have mop- or claw-like structures connected to a collar, whereas rudiviruses and tristromaviruses have plugs at each end from which bundles of thin filaments emanate.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] These protrusions are usually genus-specific, and they are made of minor structural proteins and involved in host recognition.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] Ahmunvirus and chiyouvirus virions have not been studied.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] Rudiviruses, tristromaviruses, and ungulaviruses recognize and bind to extracellular filaments during viral entry into the cell.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] For rudiviruses and tristromaviruses, these are type IV pili.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] After reaching the cell surface, rudiviruses virions disassemble, likely at the same time that viral DNA enters the host cell's cytoplasm.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] Once there, transcription of viral genes begins, starting with proteins that take over the host and defend against host immune systems, such as anti-CRISPR proteins to protect against CRISPR defense systems.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] Adnavirians do not encode their own RNA polymerases, so they rely on host transcription machinery.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] They do, however, encode proteins that regulate transcription.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] Most research on adnavirian replication has focused on rudiviruses, but it is known that adnavirians replicate through a variety of mechanisms.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] Rudiviruses encode a HUH-superfamily endonuclease, which is thought to initiate rolling circle replication by nicking DNA close to the hairpin at the end of the genome.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] For SIRV2, a rudivirus, replication occurs through a combination of strand-displacement, rolling-circle, and strand-coupled replication, which creates intermediate molecules resembling brushes that contain many copies of the genome.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] These intermediates are then processed into individual genomes.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] Acidianus filamentous virus 1, an ungulavirus, appears to start replication first by forming a D-loop, then progressing through a strand-displacement mechanism.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] Replication then ends with the help of recombination through the formation of loop-like structures.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] Classified adnavirians do not encode their own DNA polymerases, so replication is likely performed by host DNA polymerases.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] For rudiviruses, DNA polymerase B1 and a sliding clamp are involved in replication.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] Ahmunviruses encode homologs of the archaeo-eukaryotic primase and DNA polymerase sliding clamp, which likely are important during replication.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] Genes for protein-primed family B DNA polymerases have been identified by metagenomics in samples of putative adnavirians, suggesting more replication methods are used by them than what is currently known.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] Virions are assembled and enveloped in the cytoplasm.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] Characterized adnavirians replicate through the lytic cycle, leaving the cell through ruptures in the cell's external membrane (lysis).
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] Rudivirus and lipothrixvirus virions exit the cell through pyramidal structures commonly called virus-associated pyramids (VAPs).
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] VAPs are made of a small virus-encoded protein and are formed at the same time as virions.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] At the end of infection, once VAPs reach a certain size, their triangular surfaces come apart like flower petals.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] This creates openings in the cell envelope through which the contents of the cytoplasm, including virions, pour out of the cell.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] Tristromaviruses appear to use a different method of lysis during which cells are sliced open without the formation of surface structures.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] Adnavirians are known to infect hyperthermophilic (very high temperature), thermoacidophilic (high temperature, highly acidic), and methanotrophic (methane-metabolizing) archaea.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] Known and predicted hosts include thermophilic archaea of the orders Sulfolobales (rudiviruses, lipothrixviruses, ungulaviruses), Thermoproteales (tristromaviruses), and *Candidatus* Bathyarchaeales (chiyouviruses), all of which belong to the phylum Thermoproteota.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] Ahmunviruses infect anaerobic methanotrophic archaea of the class *Candidatus* Syntropharchaeia in the phylum Halobacteriota.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] Adnavirians can be found worldwide, though some, such as rudiviruses, are concentrated in extreme geothermal environments.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] Adnavirians have potentially existed for a long time, as it is thought that they may have infected the last archaeal common ancestor.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] In general, they show no genetic relation to viruses outside the realm.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] Adnavirian genes found in viruses outside the realm include those that encode glycosyltransferases, ribbon-helix-helix transcription factors, and anti-CRISPR proteins.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] Adnavirians are morphologically similar to non-archaeal filamentous viruses, but their virions are built from different capsid proteins.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] Viruses of *Clavaviridae*, a family of filamentous archaeal viruses, likewise possess MCPs and virion organization that are unrelated to the MCPs and virion organization of viruses in *Adnaviria* and for that reason are excluded from the realm.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] Viruses of *Adnaviria* began to be discovered in the 1980s by Wolfram Zillig and his colleagues.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] To discover these viruses, Zillig developed the methods used to culture their hosts.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] The first of these to be described were TTV1, TTV2, and TTV3 in 1983.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] TTV1 was classified as the first lipothrixvirus but is now classified as a tristromavirus.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] SIRV2, a rudivirus, was discovered in 1988 and has become a model for studying virus-host interactions in archaea.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] The families *Lipothrixviridae* and *Rudiviridae* were then united under the order *Ligamenvirales* in 2013 based on evidence of their relation.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] Cryogenic electron microscopy would later show in 2020 that the MCPs of tristromaviruses contained a SIRV2-like fold like ligamenviruses, which provided justification to group them together in the realm *Adnaviria*, created in 2021.
[src:alphasatellitidae/adnaviria] Before the realm was established, *Tokiviricetes*, the name of its only class, was sometimes used to refer to adnavirians.
[src:alphasatellitidae/ainoaviricetes] The genome is circular single-stranded DNA of about 9200 nucleotides in length.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] The taxonomy of this family was initially based on host range: chloroviruses infect chlorella-like green algae from freshwaters; whereas, members of the other five genera infect marine microalgae and a some species of brown macroalgae.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] This was subsequently confirmed by analysis of their B-family DNA polymerases, which indicated that members of the *Phycodnaviridae* are more closely related to one another, in comparison to other double stranded DNA viruses, forming a monophyletic group.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] The phycodnaviruses contain six genera: *Coccolithovirus, Chlorovirus, Phaeovirus, Prasinovirus,* *Prymnesiovirus* and *Raphidovirus*.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] The genera can be distinguished from one another by, for example, differences in life cycle and gene content.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] All six genera in the family *Phycodnaviridae* have similar virion structure and morphology.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] They are large virions that can range between 100 and 220 nm in diameter.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] They have a double-stranded DNA genome, and a protein core surrounded by a lipid bilayer and an icosahedral capsid.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] The capsid has 2, 3 and 5 fold axis of symmetry with 20 equilateral triangle faces composing of protein subunits.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] In all known members of the *Phycodnaviridae* the capsid is composed of ordered substructures with 20 trisymmetrons and 12 pentasymmetrons made up of donut-shaped trimeric capsomers, where each capsomer is made up of three monomers of the major capsid protein.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] If all the trimeric capsomers are identical in structure, the virion capsid contains 5040 copies of the major capsid protein in total with a triangulation number of 169.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] At the five-fold vertices there are 12 pentamer-capsomers consist of different proteins.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] The protein(s) that can be found below the axial channel of each pentamer may be responsible for digesting the host cell wall during viral infection.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] The species *Phaeocystis puchetii virus* from the genus *Prymnesiovirus* has the largest capsid structure in the *Phycodnaviridae* family.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] The lipid bilayer membrane in phycodnaviruses is not well understood or researched.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Some studies suggested that the membrane originates from the endoplasmic reticulum and may also be directly acquired from the host cell membrane during viral assembly.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Although members of the family *Phycodnaviridae* are highly diverse, they share very conserved genes involved with virion morphology or structure.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Despite the similarity of the capsid structure of phycodnaviruses, recent experiments have identified morphological differences among members in this family.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Emiliania huxleyi virus 86 (EhV-86), a coccolithovirus strain, differs from its algal virus counterparts in that its capsid is enveloped by a lipid membrane.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] In addition, recent 3D reconstruction experiments revealed that the chlorella virus PBCV-1 has a 250A-long cylindrical spike extending from one of its vertices.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] EhV-86 may also possess a spike or tail structure.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Phycodnaviruses are known for their large double-stranded DNA genomes ranging from 100kb to over 550 kb with 40% to 50% GC content.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Currently, complete genome sequences are available for several members of the family *Phycodnaviridae* (including six chloroviruses, two phaeoviruses, several prasinoviruses and a coccolithovirus) and there are also some partial sequences available for a different coccolithovirus.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] The genome structures of phycodnaviruses have considerable variation.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] The chlorovirus PBCV-1 has a linear 330 kb genome with non-permuted double-stranded DNA that is covalently closed by hairpin termini.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Similarly, the EsV-1 phaeovirus has a linear double-stranded DNA genome with inverted repeats that have almost perfect homology.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] These inverted repeats could facilitate effective circularization of the genome and for a period of time it has been suspected that EsV-1 has a circular genome.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] The EhV-86 coccolithovirus is suggested to have both linear and circular genomes at different phases during DNA packaging.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] PCR amplification reveals random A/T overhangs, detection of DNA ligases and endonucleases hinting that a linear genome may be packaged and circularizes during DNA replication.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] The phycodnaviruses have compact genomes for replication efficiency with approximately one gene per 900 to 1000 bp of genome sequences.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] The EsV-1 phaeovirus is an exception with 231 protein encoding genes, which means it has one gene per approximately 1450 bp.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] In spite of the compact genomes typically found in viruses, *Phycodnaviridae* genomes have repetitive regions usually near the terminal ends and certain tandem repeats located throughout the genome.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] It is suggested that these repetitive sequences may play a role in gene recombination that allows the virus to exchange genetic information with other viruses or the host cell.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Viruses belonging to *Phycodnaviridae* harbor double-stranded DNA genomes with sizes of several 100kbp, which together with other Megavirales (e.g.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] *Iridoviridae*, *Pandoraviridae* and *Mimiviridae*) are named nucleocytoplasmic large DNA viruses.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Because of their large genome sizes and various proteins that are encoded, viruses of *Phycodnaviridae* are challenging the traditional concepts that viruses are small and simple "organisms at the edge of life".
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] In *Raphidovirus* (likely misspelled *Rhaphidovirus*), there is only one species, *Heterosigma akashiwo virus* (HaV), which infects the unicellular alga, *Heterosigma akashiwo*.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] *H. akashiwo* is a member of the class Raphidophyceae, a bloom forming species and is widely distributed in temperate and neritic waters.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Several other types of viruses infecting *H. akashiwo* have been isolated and are not to be confused with HaV, such as the *H. akashiwo RNA virus* (HaRNAV). and *H. akashiwo* nuclear inclusion virus (HaNIV).
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] As HaV was first isolated and characterized in 1997, information about the life cycle is limited.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] HaV specifically infects *H. akashiwo* and does not infect other marine phytoplankton species tested.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] The mechanisms determining the virus-host specificity is not well understood.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] (2008) suggest that virus-host specificity maybe caused by unique interactions between a viral ligand and a host receptor.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] In a study by Nagaski et al., virus particles were found inside the host cytoplasm at 24 hours post-infection.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] The latent period or lysogenic cycle was estimated to be 30–33 h with an average burst size (number of viruses produced after lysis) of 770 per cell.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] In 2009, MacKinder et al. elucidated the entry mechanism of the genera *Coccolithovirus*.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] EhV-86 differs from its algal counterparts in that its capsid is enveloped by a lipid membrane.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] EhV-86 enters cells by endocytosis (the process by which food or liquid particles are taken into the cell by a vesicle), or direct fusion (the viral envelope fuses with the host membrane).
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] EhV-86 entry by endocytosis results in an additional membrane coat surrounding the capsid encapsulated genome.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Regardless of the mechanism of entry, the capsid enters the cytoplasm intact.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] After entering the cell, the viral capsid disassembles and the DNA is released into the host cytoplasm or directly into the nucleus.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] EhV-86 is unique to other phycodnaviruses as it encodes six RNA polymerase subunits.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Neither PBCV-1 nor ESV-1, for example encodes RNA polymerase components.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Viral RNA polymerase genes are not transcribed until at least 2 hours post infection (p.i).
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] At 3–4 p.i, virions are assembled in the cytoplasm, with the help of ATPase (a DNA packaging protein) and transported to the plasma membrane where they are released from the host via a budding mechanism.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] In this budding mechanism, EhV-86 gains an outer membrane from the host membrane.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Burst size ranges from 400 to 1000 particles per cell.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] A cluster of sphingolipid-producing genes have been identified in EhV-86.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Researchers have found that the production of viral sphingolipids produced during the lytic stage are involved in programmed cell death in coccolithophore populations.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] A high correlation was found between glycosphingolipid (GSL) production and caspase activity during the lytic stage in infected cells.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Caspases are a family of protease enzymes involved in programmed cell death.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] The researchers also found that a critical concentration of GSLs (>0.06 mg/mL) is required to initiate cell lysis.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Thus, the authors suggest that the production of GSLs to a critical concentration may be part of a timing mechanism for the lytic cycle.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] The authors also suggest that these biomolecules may be able to induce programmed cell death in other unaffected cells, thus serving as an algal bloom termination signal.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Coccolithoviruses and phaeoviruses have been described as having opposing life strategies.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] The coccolithovirus possesses an Acute life strategy characterized by high reproduction and mutation rates and greater dependency on dense host populations for transmission.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Phaeoviruses possess a Persistent life strategy where infection may or may not cause disease, and the genome is passed from parent to offspring.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Phaeoviruses infect the Ectocarpales brown algae, which is an order of filamentous brown algae.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] One of the most studied phaeoviruses is *Ectocarpus siliculosus virus*, most commonly known as EsV-1.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] The EsV-1 virus only infects the single-celled gametes or spores of E.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Vegetative cells are immune to infection, as they are protected by a rigid cell wall.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Following infection, one copy of the viral DNA is incorporated into the host genome.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] The EsV-1 viral genome is then replicated and virions are assembled in the sporangia or gametangia of infected plants.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Viruses are subsequently released via lysis of reproductive cells, stimulated by changes in environmental conditions, such as an increase in temperature.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] In healthy plants, environmental stimuli synchronize the release of gametes and zoospores into the surrounding water.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Free virus particles can then re-infect free-swimming gametes or spores of healthy plants.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Infected gametes or spores undergo mitosis, forming infected plants and all cells of the progeny plant contain viral DNA.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] However, viral particles are only produced in the reproductive cells of the algae, while viruses remain latent in vegetative cells.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] In infected sporophytes, cells undergo meiosis and produce haploid spores.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] The EsV genome is transmitted in a Mendelian manner, where half of the progeny contain viral DNA.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Often algae from infected spores are indistinguishable from algae derived from healthy spores, but are partially or fully incapable of reproduction.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Chloroviruses are the only viruses characterized thus far that infect freshwater algae.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] The hosts of chloroviruses are zoochlorellae, which are endosymbiotic green algae commonly associated with hosts *Paramecium bursaria*, coelenterate *Hydra viridis,* or the heliozoan *Acanthocystis turfacea*.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] In the ciliate *Paramecium bursaria*, for example, the algae lives within the cells of the host, providing nutrients via photosynthesis.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Living inside the cells of the ciliate offers protection for the algae, and a mode of transportation.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Zoochlorellae are resistant to infection in their symbiotic state.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] When the relationship between the algae and host is disrupted, for example, through grazing by copepods, infection by chloroviruses is permitted.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] The life cycle of the chlorovirus infecting *Paramecium bursaria*, known as PBCV-1 has been studied in detail .
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Cryo-electron microscopy and 3D reconstruction of the viral capsid shows that there is a long 'spike' structure which first contacts the cell wall and likely serves to puncture the cell wall of the host.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] The PBCV-1 virus is specific to its host and recognition is mediated by the interaction of virus surface proteins with algal surface carbohydrates.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Following attachment of the virus to the host's cell wall, capsid-bound glycolytic enzymes break down the cell wall.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] The viral membrane likely fuses with the host membrane, allowing the viral DNA to enter the cytoplasm, leaving an empty capsid on the outside.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] As PBCV-1 lacks an RNA polymerase gene, the virus must use the host cell's machinery to produce viral RNA.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Thus, the viral DNA quickly moves to the nucleus where early transcription is initiated 5–10 minutes post infection.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Within minutes of infection, host chromosomal degradation occurs, inhibiting host transcription.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] At 20 minutes post infection, most of the mRNAs in the infected cell are viral mRNAs.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] The proteins translated from the early stage of transcription are involved in initiating viral DNA replication, occurring 60–90 minutes post infection.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] The second phase of proteins are translated in the cytoplasm and the assembly of virus capsids begins about 2–3 hours post infection.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Mature virions are formed with the addition of newly replicated viral DNA from the host nucleus, likely facilitated by a virus encoded DNA packaging ATPase.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] About 5–6 hours following PBCV-1 infection, the cytoplasm is filled with virions and lysis occurs at 6–8 hours post infection releasing roughly 1000 particles per cell.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] The genus *Prymnesiovirus* currently contains only one species, known as *Chrysochromulina brevifilum* virus PW1 (CbV-PW1).
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] CbV-PW1 infects two species of marine phytoplankton, *Chrysochromulina brevifilum* and *C. strobilus*, belonging to the genus *Chrysochromulina*.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] According to the AlgaeBase database, there are currently 63 marine and freshwater species names in the genus, of which 48 are recognized as taxonomically acceptable names.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Chrysochromulina is a particularly important genus as it can comprise more than 50% of the photosynthetic nanoplanktonic cells in the ocean.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Little is known about the life cycle of the virus infecting these flagellate-containing planktonic species, *Chrysochromulina brevifilum* and *C. strobilus*.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Suttle and Chan (1995) were the first to isolate viruses which infect Prymnesiophytes or haptophytes.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] In this study, ultrathin sections of viruses within *Chyrsochromulina brevifilum* were prepared and viewed using transmission electron microscopy.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Electron micrographs in the early stage of infection suggest that virus replication occurs in the cytoplasm within a viroplasm.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] A viroplasm is a localized area in the cytoplasm, or around the nucleus of the cell which serves as a 'viral replication factory'.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] The viroplasm contains components such as virus genetic material, host proteins and ribosomes necessary for replication.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Virosomes are often surrounded by a membrane; the membrane surrounding the virosome contained in the infected cells in the study was found to consist of a fibrillar matrix.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Virions are released from infected cells following disruption of the organelles and lysis of the host cell membrane.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Suttle and Chan (1995) counted more than 320 viruses in an ultrathin section of an infection cell.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Estimates for burst sizes range from 320 to 600 viruses per cell.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Members of the genus *Prasinovirus* infect small unicellular green algae in the order Mamiellales, commonly found in coastal marine waters.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] A species of the genus *Prasinovirus* is *Micromonas pusilla virus SP1* (MpV-SP1), which was isolated from a water sample collected off of San Diego.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] The prasinovirus MpV-SP1 infects *Micromonas pusilla* which is a dominant photosynthetic marine picoeukaryote. and which infects *Micromonas pusilla* (UTEX 991, Plymouth 27).
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Common hosts of prasinoviruses include members from the genera *Ostreococcus* and *Micromonas*.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Three potential species of *Ostreococcus* have been identified and differ based on their light requirements.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] One of the most widely studied prasinoviruses, strain OtV5 whose genome is fully sequenced infects *Ostreococcus tauri*, the smallest free-living eukaryotes currently known.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Prasinoviruses employ a nucleo-cytoplasmic replication strategy where virions adhere to the host-cell surface, followed by injection of DNA into the host cytoplasm.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Researchers found that 'empty' OtV5 viruses, or viruses with only the capsid attached to the host membrane, were rarely seen at any stage of the infection, suggesting that virions detach from the host membrane after injection of their DNA.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] The authors also found that a high proportion of viruses did not attach to cells after inoculation and suggest that viral attachment may be a limiting step in the infection.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] The viral DNA is then replicated inside the nucleus by the host cell's machinery.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Virus particles are assembled in the cytoplasm, usually occupying a space near the inner face of the nucleus.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Due to the extremely small size of the algae cells, the average burst size was found to be 25 virus particles per cell.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Viral production without cell lysis has recently been observed in *O. tauri* cells.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] (2011) found that in resistant host cells, the viral genome was replicated and viruses were released via a budding mechanism.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] This low rate of viral release through budding allows for prolonged survivability of the host and virus progeny, resulting in a stable co-existence.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] PBCV-1 has a 54-kDa glycosylated major capsid protein, which comprises about 40% of total viral protein.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Therefore, the glycosylation of the major capsid protein of PBCV-1 happens independently of the ER and Golgi apparatus in host cells.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] The first known viral protein that functions as a potassium-selective ion channel was found in PBCV-1.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] The protein (called Kcv) consists of 94 amino acids and is encoded from a small open reading frame (ORF) (ORF A250R) in PBCV-1, which can produce potassium-selective and voltage-sensitive conductance in *Xenopus oocytes*.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] The supposed PBCV-1 protein has a short cytoplasmic N-terminus (12 amino acids) containing one consensus protein kinase C site and it has 2 transmembrane domains.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] The different amino acid sequences and lack of COOH-terminal cytoplasmic tail make the Kcv protein different from other potassium channels.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] EsV-1 encodes a 124 codon ORF that has significant amino acid similarity to PBCV-1 Kcv (41% amino acid identity).
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] However, the EsV-1 protein has a longer N-terminus (35 amino acids) containing two consensus protein kinase C sites and it has three transmembrane domains.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] It is unknown whether the EsV-1 protein can form a functional channel in heterologous cells.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] The EsV-1 genome also encodes several proteins with hydrophobic amino acid rich regions that resemble helical transmembrane domains.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Among these proteins, the input domain of the supposed hybrid His-kinase 186 and the ORF 188 resemble ion channel proteins.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Both EsV-1 and PBCV-1 encode DNA polymerase which belong to the DNA polymerase-δ family, and they all contain a proof-reading 3'-5' exonuclease domain.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Additionally, both PBCV-1 and EsV-1 encode a sliding clamp processivity factor protein (PCNA), which interacts with proteins involved in DNA replication as well as proteins involved in DNA repair and postreplicative processing (e.g.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Heteropentameric replication factor C (RFC) is a complex which is responsible for the ATP-dependent loading of PCNA onto DNA; EsV-1 encodes five proteins which can form a RFC complex.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] PBCV-1 encodes a single protein which resembles the found in the Archae RFC complex.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] PBCV-1 also encodes other proteins involved in DNA replication including an ATP-dependent DNA ligase, a type II DNA topoisomerase, and RNase H.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Although both EsV-1 and PBCV-1 possess genes for essential elements of the eukaryotic replication system, neither have complete replicative genes, since they all lack genes for primase.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Neither EsV-1 nor PBCV-1 encode a complete RNA polymerase, but they produce several transcription factor-like proteins to assist the host transcription system.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] EsV-1 encodes two small polypeptides (ORF 193 and ORF 196) for transcriptional regulation; the proteins resemble the α/β/α domain of TFIID-18 subunit.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] The TFIID complex is necessary for transcription of eukaryotes, as it binds to the TATA box in the core promoter of the gene to initiate the assembly of RNA polymerase.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Besides, polypeptides resemble to the SET, BTB/POZ (i.e.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Broad Complex, Tramtrack, and Bric-a-brac/poxvirus and zinc finger) (ORF 40), and BAF60b (ORF 129) domains are also encoded by ESV-1 to regulate chromatin remodeling and transcription repression.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Four transcription factor-like proteins have been found in PBSV-1, including TFIIB (A107L), TFIID (A552R), TFIIS (A125L), and a VLTF-2 type transcription factor (A482R).
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] In addition, PBCV-1 also encodes two enzymes involved in forming a mRNA cap structure, an RNA triphosphatase and a mRNA guanylyltransferase.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] The PBCV-1 enzymes are more closely related to yeast enzymes than to poxvirus multifunctional RNA capping enzymes according to its size, amino-acid sequence, and biochemical properties.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] PBCV-1 also encodes RNase III, which is involved in virus mRNAs processing.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] To supply deoxynucleotides for viral production in the low proliferating host cells, large DNA viruses possess genes to encode deoxynucleotide synthesis enzymes themselves.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Thirteen nucleotide metabolic enzymes have been found in PBCV-1, two of which include dUTP pyrophosphatase and dCMP deaminase, which can produce dUMP (i.e. the substrate for thymidylate synthetase).
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] In comparison, EsV-1 only encodes an ATPase (ORF 26) as well as both subunits of ribonucleotide reductase (ORF 128 and 180), which is a key enzyme in deoxynucleotide synthesis.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Other enzymes such as methyltransferases, DNA restriction endonucleases, and integrase were also found in PBCV-1.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] PBCV-1 also encodes a 187-amino-acid protein that resembles the Cu-Zn SOD with all of the conserved amino acid residues for binding copper and zinc, which can decompose the rapid accumulated superoxide in host cells during infection, thereby benefiting virus replication.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] The HaV virus, infecting *H. akashiwo* has been shown to be a factor in bloom termination.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] (1990) suggested that viral infection of algae could have a role in regulating population densities of phytoplankton communities, thus having significant roles in their dynamics in the oceans.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Earlier studies, such as the study by Nagasaki et al.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] (1993), explored the dynamics between HaV and *H. akashiwo*.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Algal samples were obtained in the middle or final stages of a red tide in Hiroshima Bay, Japan.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Using transmission electron microscopy, Nagaski et al. identified the HaV virus in and around the nuclear area of *H. akashiwo* cells.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Further support for the role of the HaV virus in bloom termination was provided by a study conducted by Nagaski et al.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] (1994) found that proportion of virus-containing cells increased quickly before termination of the red tide; no virus-containing cells were detected three days before termination of the red tide and the sample collected on the last day revealed a high frequency (11.5%) of virus-containing cells.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] (2000) also found an association between a decrease in cell density of *H. akashiwo* with an increase in the abundance of HaV.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] The researchers found that HaV not only plays in important role in controlling biomass, but also influences the clonal composition or characteristics of *H. akashiwo* cells.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] The researchers found that most isolates following bloom termination were resistant to HaV clonal isolates, while during bloom formation resistant cells were a minor component.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] The authors suggest that viral infection, during the bloom termination period influences the properties of dominant cells in *H. akashiwo* populations.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Selective pressure exerted by the viruses in the later stage of infection may promote genetic diversity, allowing the *H. akashiwo* population to thrive after bloom termination.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] As mentioned, *H. akashiwo* blooms are detrimental to fish populations in temperate and subarctic waters, and continue to pose serious threats for aquaculture.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] (1999) examined the growth characteristics of HaV and suggested that HaV could be used as a microbial agent against *H. akashiwo* red tides.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] The advantages of using HaV is that it specifically infects *H. akashiwo* even when other microorganisms are present.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Additionally, it has a high growth rate and can be produced at a low cost.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] The *coccolithovirus* (EhV) infects the coccolithophore *Emiliania huxleyi* (*E. huxleyi*).
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Coccolithophores are marine haptophytes which are surrounded by microscopic plates made of calcium carbonate.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] They live in the upper layers of the world's oceans and represent the third most abundant group of phytoplankton, containing about 300 species.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] *E. huxleyi* is recognized as the most prominent and ecologically important of the coccolithophores.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] *E. huxleyi* has a global distribution from the tropics to subarctic waters and occasionally forms dense blooms which can cover 100,000s of square kilometers.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] These trillions of coccolithophores produced, then die and sink to the bottom of oceans, contributing to sediment formation, and are the biggest producers of calcite in the oceans.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Thus, coccoliths have significant roles in global carbon fixation and the carbon cycle as well as sulfur cycling.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Over time, coccolithophores have shaped geological features of our planet.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] For example, the White Cliffs of Dover are formed from white chalk, or calcium carbonate produced by coccolithophores over millions of years.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Coccolithophore blooms are typically not harmful to marine life in the ocean.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] As these organisms thrive in nutrient-poor conditions, the coccolithophores offer a source of nutrition for small fish and zooplankton.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] *E. huxylei* viruses (EhVs) have been shown to be linked to the termination of these blooms.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] The termination stage of the bloom is indicated by a color change in the water.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] When large amounts of coccoliths (carbonate shell surrounding *E. huxylei*) are shed from *E. huxylei* cells from cell death or lysis, the water turns white or turquoise.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] In areas of dense bloom termination, the white color is reflective and can be seen in satellite imagery.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] (2002) used analytical flow cytometry to measure the abundance of viruses at different locations in and around the bloom area.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] The researchers found that the concentrations of viruses were higher inside the 'high reflectance area', suggesting that virus-induced lysis of E. huxleyi cells resulted in coccolith detachment.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] (1993) found higher concentrations of EhV viruses as the *E. huxleyi* bloom declined, indicating that lytic viral infection was the main cause of bloom termination.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] EhV viruses therefore have important roles in regulating biomass production in marine environments and ecological succession.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] This regulation of coccolithophore populations by EhV viruses therefore has significant effects on biogeochemical cycles, particularly the carbon cycle.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] One of the best-studied phaeoviruses, EsV-1, infects the small, filamentous brown algae *E. siliculosus*, which has a cosmopolitan distribution (found in most of the world's oceans).
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] The *Ectocarpales* are closely related to the brown algal group, the *Laminariales*, which are the most economically important group of brown algae, having a wide range of applications in the cosmetics and food industry.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] (1990) were one of the first to explore the causes of gametangium defects in *E. siliculosus* originating from New Zealand.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] The researchers identified reproductive cells of E.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] *siliculosus* filled with hexagonal particles which were then released into culture medium when the cells burst.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Following release of these particles, sporophytes became infected, shown by pathological symptoms, suggesting that the particles are viruses.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Such studies allowed for the evaluation of infection potential of E.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Using PCR amplification of a viral gene fragment, Muller et al.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] (2005) monitored levels of pathogen infection in *Ectocarpus* samples from the Gran Canaria Island, North Atlantic and southern Chile.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] The researchers found high levels of pathogen prevalence; 40–100% of *Ectocarpus* specimens contained viral DNA.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Similar estimates have been given by Sengco et al.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] (1996) who estimated that at least 50% of *Ectocarpus* plants in the world contain viral DNA.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] This high frequency of viral infection among globally distributed *Ectocarpus* plants has ecological implications.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Viral infection by EsV-1 in *E. siliculosus* plants, as mentioned, limits reproductive success of infected plants.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Thus, the EsV-1 virus plays a key role in regulating populations of *E. siliculosus*, having further effects on local ecosystem dynamics.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Members of the genus *Chlorovirus* are found in freshwater sources around the world and infect the green algae symbionts zoochlorellae.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] There is a lack of information about the role chloroviruses play in freshwater ecology.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Despite this, chloroviruses are found in native waters at 1–100 plaque-forming units (PFU)/mL and measurements as high as 100,000 PFU/mL of native water have been obtained.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] A plaque-forming unit is the number of particles capable of forming visible structures within a cell culture, known as plaques.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Abundances of chloroviruses vary with season, with the highest abundances occurring in the spring.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Chloroviruses, such as PBCV-1, play a role in regulating host populations of zoochlorella.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] As mentioned previously, infection of zoochlorella occurs only when the symbiotic relationship with its host is disrupted.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Chloroviruses and viruses in general cause death and lysis of their hosts, releasing dissolved organic carbon, nitrogen and phosphorus into the water.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] These nutrients can then be taken up by bacteria, thus contributing to the microbial loop.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Liberation of dissolved organic materials allows for bacterial growth, and bacteria are an important source of food for organisms in higher trophic levels.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Consequently, chloroviruses have significant effects on carbon and nutrient flows, influencing freshwater ecosystem dynamics.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Prymnesiovirus, CbV-PW1, as mentioned infects the algal genus *Chyrsochromulina*.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] *Chyrsochromulina*, found in global fresh and marine waters, occasionally forms dense blooms which can produce harmful toxins, having negative effects on fisheries.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] *polylepis* has caused enormous damage to commercial fisheries in Scandinavia.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] In 1988, this bloom caused a loss of 500 tons of caged fish, worth 5 million US.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Given that *Chyrsochromulina* is a widespread species, and is of significant ecological importance, viral infection and lysis of genus members is likely to have significant impacts on biogeochemical cycles, such as nutrient recycling in aquatic environments.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Suttle and Chan suggest that the presence of viruses should have a strong regulatory effect on *Chyrsochromulina* populations, thus preventing bloom formation or enabling bloom termination, explaining why persistent blooms are an unusual phenomenon in nature.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] A commonly studied prasinovirus, OtV5, as mentioned, infects the smallest currently known eukaryote, *Ostreococcus tauri*.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] *O. tauri* is about 0.8 micrometers in diameter and is within the picosize fraction (0.2–2 micrometers).
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Picoeukaryotes, such as *Ostreococcus tauri* are widely distributed and contribute significantly to microbial biomass and total primary productivity.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] In oligotrophic environments, marine picophytoplankton account for up to 90% of the autotrophic biomass and thus are an important food source for nanoplanktonic and phagotrophic protists.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] As picoeukaryotes serve as the base for marine microbial food webs, they are intrinsic to the survival of higher trophic levels.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] *Ostreococcus tauri* has a rapid growth rate and dense blooms have been observed off the coasts of Long Island and California.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Samples collected from Long Island bay were found to contain many virus-like particles, a likely cause for the decline of the bloom.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Despite the large abundances of picoeukaryotes, these unicellular organisms are outnumbered by viruses by about ten to one.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Viruses such as OtV5, play important roles in regulating phytoplankton populations, and through lysis of cells contribute to the recycling of nutrients back towards other microorganisms, otherwise known as the viral shunt.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] As mentioned, the prasinovirus MpV-SP1 infects *Micromonas pusilla* which is a major component of the picophytoplankton of the world's oceans.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] *M. pusilla* lives from tropical to polar marine ecosystems.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Cottrell & Suttle (1995) found that 2–10% of the *M. pusilla* population in an inshore environment was lysed per day, with an average of 4.4%.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Higher estimates have been given by Evans et al.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] *pusilla* viruses can lyse up to 25% of the *Micromonas* population per day.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] This suggests that viruses are responsible for a moderate amount of mortality in M.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] On a larger scale, viral infection of *M. pusilla* is responsible for nutrient and energy recycling in aquatic food webs, which is yet to be quantified.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Until recently phycodnaviruses were believed to infect algal species exclusively.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Recently, DNA homologous to Chlorovirus Acanthocystis turfacea virus 1 (ATCV-1) were isolated from human nasopharyngeal mucosal surfaces.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] The presence of ATCV-1 in the human microbiome was associated with diminished performance on cognitive assessments.
[src:alphasatellitidae/algavirales] Inoculation of ATCV-1 in experimental animals was associated with decreased performance in memory and sensory-motor gating, as well as altered expression of genes in the hippocampus related to synaptic plasticity, learning, memory formation, and the viral immune response.
[src:alphasatellitidae/alphasatellitidae] These viruses were earlier known as DNA 1 components.
[src:alphasatellitidae/alphasatellitidae] These viruses are generally found in the Old World.
[src:alphasatellitidae/alphasatellitidae] A number have been isolated from the New World but their association with their host viruses is still being studied.
[src:alphasatellitidae/alphasatellitidae] The genome is between 1300 and 1400 nucleotides in length and has three conserved features: a hairpin structure, a single open reading frame (ORF) and an adenine rich region.
[src:alphasatellitidae/alphasatellitidae] The hairpin structure has a loop that includes the nonanucleotide, TAGTATTAC, which is common to nanoviruses and differs from the TAATATTAC sequence of geminiviruses by one nucleotide.
[src:alphasatellitidae/alphasatellitidae] In both geminiviruses and nanoviruses this sequence contains the origin of replication (*ori*) and is nicked by the rolling circle replication initiator protein to initiate viral DNA replication.
[src:alphasatellitidae/alphasatellitidae] On the basis of the hairpin structures alphasatellites can be divided into 5 clades.
[src:alphasatellitidae/alphasatellitidae] The open reading frame encodes a rolling circle replication initiator protein (Rep) similar to that found in the nanoviruses.
[src:alphasatellitidae/alphasatellitidae] The encoded protein is about 36.6 kilodalton in molecular weight with about 315 amino acids.
[src:alphasatellitidae/alphasatellitidae] It is highly conserved with 86.3–100.0% amino acid sequence identity between isolates.
[src:alphasatellitidae/alphasatellitidae] The adenine rich region is immediately downstream of the *rep* gene and is approximately 153–169 nucleotides in length with an adenine content of between 52.3–58.4%.
[src:alphasatellitidae/alphasatellitidae] Phylogenectic analysis of this region shows that they can be divided into three clades which correspond to those found on phylogenetic analysis of the entire genome.
[src:alphasatellitidae/alphasatellitidae] This portion of the genome appears to be redundant.
[src:alphasatellitidae/alphasatellitidae] A putative second ORF in the genome of an alphasatellite virus has been described.
[src:alphasatellitidae/alphasatellitidae] The significance of this finding (if any) is not known.
[src:alphasatellitidae/alphasatellitidae] Recombination occurs between alphasatellites.
[src:alphasatellitidae/alphasatellitidae] There are no distinctive virions because the viral genomes are encapsidated within the coat protein of the helper virus.
[src:alphasatellitidae/alphasatellitidae] Alphasatellites associated with the begomoviruses require a begomovirus for movement in plants and insect transmission but are capable of self replication in host plants.
[src:alphasatellitidae/alphasatellitidae] They do not appear to cause disease in plants or to alter the course of infection by the begomovirus.
[src:alphasatellitidae/alphasatellitidae] They may be able to reduce the severity of an infection by the begomoviruses.
[src:alphasatellitidae/alphasatellitidae] Alphasatellites have also been described in association with *Nanoviridae*.
[src:alphasatellitidae/alphasatellitidae] These tend to be slightly shorter (1100–1300 nucleotides) but to encode proteins in addition to the *rep* gene.
[src:alphasatellitidae/alphasatellitidae] Because of the multiple component genome of the *Nanoviridae* these were not initially recognised as distinct genomes.
[src:alphasatellitidae/alphasatellitidae] Alphasatellites may be the target of RNA silencing.
[src:alphasatellitidae/alphasatellitidae] Alphasatellites are grouped together in the family *Alphasatellitidae*.
[src:alphasatellitidae/alphasatellitidae] This family has three subfamilies and 20 genera.
[src:alphasatellitidae/alphasatellitidae] Given the similarities between the *rep* proteins of the alphasatellites and the nanoviruses, it is likely that the alphasatellites evolved from the nanoviruses.
[src:alphasatellitidae/alphasatellitidae] These viruses have been used in the development of viral gene silencing studies.
